{"title_page": "Elvis (musical)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox Musical\n|name= \"Elvis\" - The Musical\n|image= Elvis the musical.jpg\n|caption= Original London Cast Recording\n|music= Various Artists\n|lyrics= Various Artists\n|book= [[Jack Good (producer)|Jack Good]] <br> [[Ray Cooney]]\n|basis= The life and music of [[Elvis Presley]]\n|productions= 1977 [[West End theatre|West End]]\n1996 [[West End theatre|West End]]\n<!-- Please do not include production-specific (acting, directing, etc.) awards -->\n|awards= \n}}\n'''''Elvis''''' is a [[jukebox musical]] based upon the life of [[Elvis Presley]], conceived and directed by [[Jack Good (producer)|Jack Good]] (Director and Co-devisor) and [[Ray Cooney]] (Producer and Co-Devisor).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.strachan.org/elvis-77.html|title=Elvis 77|website=Keith Strachan|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> It tells the story of Elvis Presley's life and career, from the beginning until his death. The original cast included [[Shakin' Stevens]], who later became the top-selling UK singles artist of the 1980s and Tracey Ullman.<ref>{{cite news|author=Caroline Sullivan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/dec/22/popandrock2?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Shakin' Stevens, Shepherd's Bush Empire, London &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date= 22 December 2005|accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==Production history==\n\n===1977 production===\nThe original [[West End theatre|West End]] production opened on November 28, 1977 at the [[Astoria Theatre]] in [[London]] which had been converted from being a Cinema especially for the show by Laurie Marsh.<ref>Souvenir programme for \"Elvis\"</ref> Elvis was portrayed by four actors over the course of its run: [[Tim Whitnall]] as Elvis in his early years; [[Shakin' Stevens]] as Elvis in his [[United States Army|army]] and [[Elvis Presley filmography|movie star]] years; and [[PJ Proby]] as Elvis in his [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] years, and later was played by [[Mr. Lee Grant|Bogdan Kominowski]]. Live musical accompaniment was provided by the [[rock and roll revival]] group, [[Fumble (band)|Fumble]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fumble|first1=Angie|title=FUMBLE in Elvis \u2013 The Musical|url=http://www.fumbleontheweb.com/sites/elvis.htm|website=www.fumbleontheweb.com|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> Overthefootlights.co.uk records that it played for 614 performances, indicating that the show closed in late April 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.overthefootlights.co.uk/1977musicals.pdf|title=London Shows 1977|last=|first=|date=|website=Over The Footlights|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (This can be confirmed by the fact that many of the cast went on to perform in the 1979 revival of Grease which previewed at the Bristol Hippodrome in May 1979).<ref>{{cite web|title=Grease (London Revival, 1979)|url=http://www.ovrtur.com/production/2891414|website=www.ovrtur.com|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> The show later went on for a National and European Tour, opening in Bournemouth in December 1979 with Shakin' Stevens and Bogdan Kominowski resuming their roles as middle and older Elvis, Stevens signing only for the tour's opening weeks. Vince Eager later replaced Kominowski on tour.\n\n====Production team====\n*Producer and co-devisor - [[Ray Cooney]]\n*Director and co-devisor - [[Jack Good (producer)|Jack Good]]\n*Designer - Patrick Robertson\n*Lighting - [[David Hersey]]\n*Costumes - [[Rosemary Vercoe]]\n*Sound - Autograph\n*AV - Ray Millichope\n*Musical Director - [[Keith Strachan]]\n*Musical Supervisor and co-writer - [[Harry Robinson (musician)|Harry Robinson]]\n*Assistant director - Annabel Leventon\n*Choreographer - Carole Todd\n\n====Cast====\n*[[PJ Proby]] (listed as James Proby in programme) - Older Elvis (later replaced by Bogdan Kominowski)\n*[[Mr. Lee Grant|Bogdan Kominowski]] - Older Elvis\n*[[Shakin' Stevens]] - Middle Elvis\n*[[Tim Whitnall]] - Young Elvis\n*Helen Baker - Singer and Dancer\n*Tanith Banbury - Singer and Dancer\n*Anna Macleod - Singer and Dancer\n*Yael O'Dwyer - Singer and Dancer\n*[[Tracey Ullman]] - Dance Captain and Singer / Dancer\n*Richard Ashley - Singer and Dancer \n*Paul Felber - Singer and Dancer\n*Stephen Leigh - Singer and Dancer\n*Richard Piper - Singer and Dancer\n*Shaun Simon - Singer and Dancer\n\n====Musicians====\n*[[Keith Strachan]]<ref>[http://www.strachan.org/theatre.html Keith Strachan] Musical director of 1977 production and co-director of 1996 production.</ref> (MD)\n*[[Sean Mayes]]\n*[[Fumble (band)|Mario Ferrari]]\n*[[Fumble (band)|Des Henly]]\n*[[Fumble (band)|Barry Pike]]\n*[[Ronnie Caryl]]\n*Bob Efford\n*Roy Truman\n*Paul Urwin\n*Mike Harding\n*Tony Hepworth\n*Mark Hutchins\n*Phil Todd\n\n===1996 production===\nIn 1996, [[Bill Kenwright]] Ltd mounted a modified production at the [[Prince Of Wales Theatre]], directed by Keith Strachan and Carole Todd. PJ Proby returned as Las Vegas Elvis, Tim Whitnall as mid-period Elvis, and Alexander Bar<ref>[http://www.alexanderbar.me/elvis.html Alexander Bar]</ref> joined them as young Elvis. Various song changes were made to the initial 1977 production. After transferring to the [[Piccadilly Theatre]] in 1997, the show toured the UK until 2000.\n\n==Musical numbers<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.musicalheaven.com/Detailed/1106.html |title=MusicalHeaven.com |access-date=2009-12-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729184904/http://www.musicalheaven.com/Detailed/1106.html |archive-date=2010-07-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>==\n*[[Jerry Reed|Tupelo Mississippi Flash]]\n*[[Blue Suede Shoes]]\n*[[Are You Lonesome Tonight? (song)|Are You Lonesome Tonight?]]\n*[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\n*[[A World Without Love]]\n*[[Mystery Train]]\n*[[Tiger Man (album)|Tiger Man]]\n*[[Loving You (Elvis Presley song)|Loving You]]\n*[[I Want To Hold Your Hand]]\n*All Round The World\n*[[Six-Five Special]]\n*[[How Great Thou Art (hymn)|How Great Thou Art]]\n*[[King Creole (song)|King Creole]]\n*[[King Creole (soundtrack)|Dixieland Rock]]\n*[[Got a Lot o' Livin' to Do!|Got A Lot O' Livin' To Do]]\n*[[Wear My Ring Around Your Neck]]\n*[[Ready Teddy]]\n*[[Let's Have a Party]]\n*[[Tryin' to Get to You]]\n*[[Too Much (Elvis Presley song)|Too Much]]\n*[[Teddy Bear (song)|Teddy Bear]]\n*[[Such a Night]]\n*[[Don't (Elvis Presley song)|Don't]]\n*[[Good Luck Charm]]\n*[[Return to Sender (song)|Return to Sender]]\n*[[Burning Love]]\n*[[My Baby Left Me]]\n*[[One Night (Elvis Presley song)|One Night]]\n*[[Treat Me Nice]]\n*[[Mean Woman Blues]]\n*[[Hound Dog (song)|Hound Dog]]\n*[[Jailhouse Rock (song)|Jailhouse Rock]]\n*[[An American Trilogy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fumbleontheweb.com/sites/elvis.htm Fumble] Site devoted to the original [[house band]].\n*[http://www.alexanderbar.me/elvis.html Alexander Bar] Site maintained by a star of the 1996 production, featuring [[Clipping (publications)|clippings]], photographs and promotional appearances.\n\n{{Elvis Presley}}\n\n\n[[Category:1977 musicals]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musicals]]\n[[Category:West End musicals]]\n[[Category:British musicals]]\n[[Category:Rock musicals]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Elvis Presley]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox Musical\n|name= \"Elvis\" - The Musical\n|image= Elvis the musical.jpg\n|caption= Original London Cast Recording\n|music= Various Artists\n|lyrics= Various Artists\n|book= [[Jack Good (producer)|Jack Good]] <br> [[Ray Cooney]]\n|basis= The life and music of [[Elvis Presley]]\n|productions= 1977 [[West End theatre|West End]]\n1996 [[West End theatre|West End]]\n<!-- Please do not include production-specific (acting, directing, etc.) awards -->\n|awards= \n}}\n'''''Elvis''''' is a [[jukebox musical]] based upon the life of [[Elvis Presley]], conceived and directed by [[Jack Good (producer)|Jack Good]] (Director and Co-devisor) and [[Ray Cooney]] (Producer and Co-Devisor).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.strachan.org/elvis-77.html|title=Elvis 77|website=Keith Strachan|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> It tells the story of Elvis Presley's life and career, from the beginning until his death. The original cast included [[Shakin' Stevens]], who later became the top-selling UK singles artist of the 1980s and Tracey Ullman.<ref>{{cite news|author=Caroline Sullivan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/dec/22/popandrock2?INTCMP=SRCH |title=Shakin' Stevens, Shepherd's Bush Empire, London &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date= 22 December 2005|accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==Production history==\n\n===1977 production===\nThe original [[West End theatre|West End]] production opened on November 28, 1977 at the [[Astoria Theatre]] in [[London]] which had been converted from being a Cinema especially for the show by Laurie Marsh.<ref>Souvenir programme for \"Elvis\"</ref> Elvis was portrayed by four actors over the course of its run: [[Tim Whitnall]] as Elvis in his early years; [[Shakin' Stevens]] as Elvis in his [[United States Army|army]] and [[Elvis Presley filmography|movie star]] years; and [[PJ Proby]] as Elvis in his [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] years, and later was played by [[Mr. Lee Grant|Bogdan Kominowski]]. Live musical accompaniment was provided by the [[rock and roll revival]] group, [[Fumble (band)|Fumble]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fumble|first1=Angie|title=FUMBLE in Elvis \u2013 The Musical|url=http://www.fumbleontheweb.com/sites/elvis.htm|website=www.fumbleontheweb.com|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> Overthefootlights.co.uk records that it played for 614 performances, indicating that the show closed in late April 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.overthefootlights.co.uk/1977musicals.pdf|title=London Shows 1977|last=|first=|date=|website=Over The Footlights|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (This can be confirmed by the fact that many of the cast went on to perform in the 1979 revival of Grease which previewed at the Bristol Hippodrome in May 1979).<ref>{{cite web|title=Grease (London Revival, 1979)|url=http://www.ovrtur.com/production/2891414|website=www.ovrtur.com|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> The show later went on for a National and European Tour, opening in Bournemouth in December 1979 with Shakin' Stevens and Bogdan Kominowski resuming their roles as middle and older Elvis.\n\n====Production team====\n*Producer and co-devisor - [[Ray Cooney]]\n*Director and co-devisor - [[Jack Good (producer)|Jack Good]]\n*Designer - Patrick Robertson\n*Lighting - [[David Hersey]]\n*Costumes - [[Rosemary Vercoe]]\n*Sound - Autograph\n*AV - Ray Millichope\n*Musical Director - [[Keith Strachan]]\n*Musical Supervisor and co-writer - [[Harry Robinson (musician)|Harry Robinson]]\n*Assistant director - Annabel Leventon\n*Choreographer - Carole Todd\n\n====Cast====\n*[[PJ Proby]] (listed as James Proby in programme) - Older Elvis (later replaced by Bogdan Kominowski)\n*[[Mr. Lee Grant|Bogdan Kominowski]] - Older Elvis\n*[[Shakin' Stevens]] - Middle Elvis\n*[[Tim Whitnall]] - Young Elvis\n*Helen Baker - Singer and Dancer\n*Tanith Banbury - Singer and Dancer\n*Anna Macleod - Singer and Dancer\n*Yael O'Dwyer - Singer and Dancer\n*[[Tracey Ullman]] - Dance Captain and Singer / Dancer\n*Richard Ashley - Singer and Dancer \n*Paul Felber - Singer and Dancer\n*Stephen Leigh - Singer and Dancer\n*Richard Piper - Singer and Dancer\n*Shaun Simon - Singer and Dancer\n\n====Musicians====\n*[[Keith Strachan]]<ref>[http://www.strachan.org/theatre.html Keith Strachan] Musical director of 1977 production and co-director of 1996 production.</ref> (MD)\n*[[Sean Mayes]]\n*[[Fumble (band)|Mario Ferrari]]\n*[[Fumble (band)|Des Henly]]\n*[[Fumble (band)|Barry Pike]]\n*[[Ronnie Caryl]]\n*Bob Efford\n*Roy Truman\n*Paul Urwin\n*Mike Harding\n*Tony Hepworth\n*Mark Hutchins\n*Phil Todd\n\n===1996 production===\nIn 1996, [[Bill Kenwright]] Ltd mounted a modified production at the [[Prince Of Wales Theatre]], directed by Keith Strachan and Carole Todd. PJ Proby returned as Las Vegas Elvis, Tim Whitnall as mid-period Elvis, and Alexander Bar<ref>[http://www.alexanderbar.me/elvis.html Alexander Bar]</ref> joined them as young Elvis. Various song changes were made to the initial 1977 production. After transferring to the [[Piccadilly Theatre]] in 1997, the show toured the UK until 2000.\n\n==Musical numbers<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.musicalheaven.com/Detailed/1106.html |title=MusicalHeaven.com |access-date=2009-12-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729184904/http://www.musicalheaven.com/Detailed/1106.html |archive-date=2010-07-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>==\n*[[Jerry Reed|Tupelo Mississippi Flash]]\n*[[Blue Suede Shoes]]\n*[[Are You Lonesome Tonight? (song)|Are You Lonesome Tonight?]]\n*[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\n*[[A World Without Love]]\n*[[Mystery Train]]\n*[[Tiger Man (album)|Tiger Man]]\n*[[Loving You (Elvis Presley song)|Loving You]]\n*[[I Want To Hold Your Hand]]\n*All Round The World\n*[[Six-Five Special]]\n*[[How Great Thou Art (hymn)|How Great Thou Art]]\n*[[King Creole (song)|King Creole]]\n*[[King Creole (soundtrack)|Dixieland Rock]]\n*[[Got a Lot o' Livin' to Do!|Got A Lot O' Livin' To Do]]\n*[[Wear My Ring Around Your Neck]]\n*[[Ready Teddy]]\n*[[Let's Have a Party]]\n*[[Tryin' to Get to You]]\n*[[Too Much (Elvis Presley song)|Too Much]]\n*[[Teddy Bear (song)|Teddy Bear]]\n*[[Such a Night]]\n*[[Don't (Elvis Presley song)|Don't]]\n*[[Good Luck Charm]]\n*[[Return to Sender (song)|Return to Sender]]\n*[[Burning Love]]\n*[[My Baby Left Me]]\n*[[One Night (Elvis Presley song)|One Night]]\n*[[Treat Me Nice]]\n*[[Mean Woman Blues]]\n*[[Hound Dog (song)|Hound Dog]]\n*[[Jailhouse Rock (song)|Jailhouse Rock]]\n*[[An American Trilogy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fumbleontheweb.com/sites/elvis.htm Fumble] Site devoted to the original [[house band]].\