{"title_page": "Misconduct", "text_new": "{{short description|Legal term; form of wrongful, improper, or unlawful conduct}}\n{{About|the legal sense|misconduct in scientific research|scientific misconduct|the [[association football]] sense|fouls and misconduct (association football)|the infraction in ice hockey|penalty (ice hockey)|the 2016 American film|Misconduct (film)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|date=December 2014}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2014}}}}\nIn law, '''misconduct''' is wrongful, improper, or unlawful conduct motivated by premeditated or intentional purpose or by obstinate indifference to the consequences of one's acts. Misconduct can be considered an unacceptable or improper behavior, especially for a professional person. Two categories of misconduct are [[sexual misconduct]] and [[official misconduct]]. In connection with school discipline, \"misconduct\" is generally understood to be student behavior that is unacceptable to school officials but does not violate criminal statutes, including [[absenteeism]], tardiness, [[bullying]], and inappropriate language. (Special Education Dictionary, 2003, LRP Publications) Misconduct in the  workplace generally falls under two categories. Minor misconduct is seen as unacceptable but is not a criminal offense (e.g. being late, faking qualifications).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medico-legalsociety.org.uk/articles/dishonesty_in_medical_research.pdf |format=PDF |title=Dishonesty in Medical Research |publisher=Medico-legalsociety.org.uk |accessdate=1 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521050439/http://www.medico-legalsociety.org.uk/articles/dishonesty_in_medical_research.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2013 }}</ref> Gross misconduct can lead to dismissal (e.g. stealing or sexual harassment).\n\n* \"Misconduct\" includes something seen as unacceptable as well as criminal offenses e.g. deceptive manipulation.\n* \"Gross misconduct\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Gross Misconduct|work=Access Solicitor|url=http://www.accesssolicitor.com/glossary/employment-law/disciplinary-and-procedures/gross-misconduct/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218073045/http://www.accesssolicitor.com/glossary/employment-law/disciplinary-and-procedures/gross-misconduct/|archivedate=February 18, 2013}}</ref> can lead to immediate dismissal because it is serious enough and possibly criminal, e.g. [[stealing]] or [[sexual harassment]].\n\nMisconduct refers to an action, rather than neglecting to take action, or inaction which could be referred to as poor performance.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\n==Examples of gross misconduct==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2019}}\nThe following may be classified as gross misconduct:\n* Being drunk or under the influence of any drug while on duty\n* Bribery\n* Conviction of a felony (in some jurisdictions)\n* Falsification of accounts\n* Falsifying time records\n* Financial misconduct\n* Fighting\n* Gross insubordination/disobedience/misappropriation\n* Illegal drug or alcohol use at work\n* Illicit use{{clarifyme|date=January 2020}}\n* Negligence\n* Sexual harassment in the workplace\n* Stealing\n* Subjecting people to discrimination\n\n== Organizational ==\nOrganization and management scholars have paid much attention to the causes, forms, modes of development, and consequences of misconduct within or among organizations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Greve|first=Henrich R.|last2=Palmer|first2=Donald|last3=Pozner|first3=Jo\u2010Ellen|date=2010|title=Organizations Gone Wild: The Causes, Processes, and Consequences of Organizational Misconduct|url=http://journals.aom.org/doi/10.5465/19416521003654186|journal=Academy of Management Annals|language=en|volume=4|issue=1|pages=53\u2013107|doi=10.5465/19416521003654186|issn=1941-6520|via=}}</ref> They have studied different types of misconduct, such as [[White-collar crime|white-collar crimes]], [[insider trading]], or deceptive accounting<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harris|first=Jared|last2=Bromiley|first2=Philip|date=2007|title=Incentives to Cheat: The Influence of Executive Compensation and Firm Performance on Financial Misrepresentation|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/25146106|journal=Organization Science|volume=18|issue=3|pages=350\u2013367|issn=1047-7039}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zahra|first=Shaker A.|last2=Priem|first2=Richard L.|last3=Rasheed|first3=Abdul A.|date=2005|title=The Antecedents and Consequences of Top Management Fraud|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/doi/10.1177/0149206305279598|journal=Journal of Management|language=en-US|volume=31|issue=6|pages=803\u2013828|doi=10.1177/0149206305279598|issn=0149-2063|via=}}</ref> and, more recently, considered the development of misconduct activities between different firms, such as [[Cartel|cartels]] where firms reduce competition by agreeing on production or pricing. It has then been argued that the organization of misconduct across different firms present unique challenges to conceal activities or maintain collective secret.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bertrand|first=Olivier|last2=Lumineau|first2=Fabrice|date=2016|title=Partners in Crime: The Effects of Diversity on the Longevity of Cartels|url=https://journals.aom.org/doi/10.5465/amj.2013.1209|journal=Academy of Management Journal|volume=59|issue=3|pages=983\u20131008|doi=10.5465/amj.2013.1209|issn=0001-4273|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Financial==\nThe failure to understand and manage [[ethical]] risks played a significant role in the financial crisis. The difference between bad business decisions and [[business]] misconduct can be hard to determine, and there is a thin line between the ethics of using only financial incentives to gauge performance and the use of holistic measures that include ethics, transparency and responsibility of [[stakeholder (corporate)|stakeholder]]s. From CEO's to traders and brokers, all-too-tempting lucrative financial incentives existed for performance in the financial industry.<br />\nThe past widespread financial misconduct led to a call for financial reform. The [[Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]]  was passed in 2010 to increase accountability and transparency in the financial industry and protect consumers from deceptive financial practices.<ref>Ferrell, Fraedrich: ''Business Ethics'', ''eleventh edition'' Ethical Decision Making and Case, Sexual Harassment in Workplace. February 17, 2017. p. 80</ref> [[Domestic inquiry]]  A domestic inquiry typically follows a \u2018show cause\u2019 letter, which is sent to the employee requesting an explanation for the alleged misconduct. If the response is not satisfactory, the employer will move to the more formal domestic inquiry. Domestic inquiry should be carried out as soon as possible following accusations of misconduct and all activities should be formalized and recorded in full. Legally it is important than the investigation be carried out objectively \u2013 the investigating officers, for example, should be unconnected to the incident, and the employee should be given full opportunity to state their own case and present evidence in their favor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pesaraonline.net/domestic-inquiry.htm|title=Domestic Inquiry|website=pesaraonline.net|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> Union representatives or colleagues should be allowed to sit in during the process if the employer requests their presence, although the employee can't insist on legal representation. An employer may, on the grounds of misconduct inconsistent with the fulfillment of the express or implied conditions of his services, after due inquiry:\n# dismiss without notice the employee\n# downgrade the employee\n# impose any other lesser punishment as he deems just and fit, and where a punishment of suspension without wages is imposed, it shall not exceed a period of two weeks.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* {{cite book |last = Ghaiye |first = B. R. |title = Misconduct in Employment |publisher=EBC |ISBN = 9789351450252 |edition = Hardbound }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{cite news |publisher=FBI |work=Law Enforcement Bulletin |url = https://www.fbi.gov/stats-services/publications/law-enforcement-bulletin/2013/March/research-forum |date=March 2013 |title=Research Forum }}\n\n{{-}}\n{{abuse}}\n\n[[Category:Misconduct| ]]\n[[Category:Legal terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Legal term; form of wrongful, improper, or unlawful conduct}}\n{{About|the legal sense|misconduct in scientific research|scientific misconduct|the [[association football]] sense|fouls and misconduct (association football)|the infraction in ice hockey|penalty (ice hockey)|the 2016 American film|Misconduct (film)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|date=December 2014}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2014}}}}\nIn law, '''misconduct''' is wrongful, improper, or unlawful conduct motivated by premeditated or intentional purpose or by obstinate indifference to the consequences of one's acts. Misconduct can be considered an unacceptable or improper behavior, especially for a professional person. Two categories of misconduct are [[sexual misconduct]] and [[official misconduct]]. In connection with school discipline, \"misconduct\" is generally understood to be student behavior that is unacceptable to school officials but does not violate criminal statutes, including [[absenteeism]], tardiness, [[bullying]], and inappropriate language. (Special Education Dictionary, 2003, LRP Publications) Misconduct in the  workplace generally falls under two categories. Minor misconduct is seen as unacceptable but is not a criminal offense (e.g. being late, faking qualifications).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medico-legalsociety.org.uk/articles/dishonesty_in_medical_research.pdf |format=PDF |title=Dishonesty in Medical Research |publisher=Medico-legalsociety.org.uk |accessdate=1 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521050439/http://www.medico-legalsociety.org.uk/articles/dishonesty_in_medical_research.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2013 }}</ref> Gross misconduct can lead to dismissal (e.g. stealing or sexual harassment).\n\n* \"Misconduct\" includes something seen as unacceptable as well as criminal offenses e.g. deceptive manipulation.\n* \"Gross misconduct\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Gross Misconduct|work=Access Solicitor|url=http://www.accesssolicitor.com/glossary/employment-law/disciplinary-and-procedures/gross-misconduct/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218073045/http://www.accesssolicitor.com/glossary/employment-law/disciplinary-and-procedures/gross-misconduct/|archivedate=February 18, 2013}}</ref> can lead to immediate dismissal because it is serious enough and possibly criminal, e.g. [[stealing]] or [[sexual harassment]].\n\nMisconduct refers to an action, rather than neglecting to take action, or inaction which could be referred to as poor performance.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\n==Examples of gross misconduct==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2019}}\nThe following may be classified as gross misconduct:\n* Being drunk or under the influence of any drug while on duty\n* Bribery\n* Conviction of a felony (in some jurisdictions)\n* Falsification of accounts\n* Falsifying time records\n* Financial misconduct\n* Fighting\n* Gross insubordination/disobedience/misappropriation\n* Illegal drug or alcohol use at work\n* Illicit use{{clarifyme|date=January 2020}}\n* Negligence\n* Sexual harassment in the workplace\n* Stealing\n* Subjecting people to discrimination\n\n== Organizational ==\nOrganization and management scholars have paid much attention to the causes, forms, modes of development, and consequences of misconduct within or among organizations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Greve|first=Henrich R.|last2=Palmer|first2=Donald|last3=Pozner|first3=Jo\u2010Ellen|date=2010|title=Organizations Gone Wild: The Causes, Processes, and Consequences of Organizational Misconduct|url=http://journals.aom.org/doi/10.5465/19416521003654186|journal=Academy of Management Annals|language=en|volume=4|issue=1|pages=53\u2013107|doi=10.5465/19416521003654186|issn=1941-6520|via=}}</ref> They have studied different types of misconduct, such as white-collar crimes, insider trading, or deceptive accounting<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harris|first=Jared|last2=Bromiley|first2=Philip|date=2007|title=Incentives to Cheat: The Influence of Executive Compensation and Firm Performance on Financial Misrepresentation|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/25146106|journal=Organization Science|volume=18|issue=3|pages=350\u2013367|issn=1047-7039}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zahra|first=Shaker A.|last2=Priem|first2=Richard L.|last3=Rasheed|first3=Abdul A.|date=2005|title=The Antecedents and Consequences of Top Management Fraud|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/doi/10.1177/0149206305279598|journal=Journal of Management|language=en-US|volume=31|issue=6|pages=803\u2013828|doi=10.1177/0149206305279598|issn=0149-2063|via=}}</ref> and, more recently, considered the development of misconduct activities between different firms, such as cartels where firms reduce competition by agreeing on production or pricing. It has then been argued that the organization of misconduct across different firms present unique challenges to conceal activities or maintain collective secret.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bertrand|first=Olivier|last2=Lumineau|first2=Fabrice|date=2016|title=Partners in Crime: The Effects of Diversity on the Longevity of Cartels|url=https://journals.aom.org/doi/10.5465/amj.2013.1209|journal=Academy of Management Journal|volume=59|issue=3|pages=983\u20131008|doi=10.5465/amj.2013.1209|issn=0001-4273|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Financial==\nThe failure to understand and manage [[ethical]] risks played a significant role in the financial crisis. The difference between bad business decisions and [[business]] misconduct can be hard to determine, and there is a thin line between the ethics of using only financial incentives to gauge performance and the use of holistic measures that include ethics, transparency and responsibility of [[stakeholder (corporate)|stakeholder]]s. From CEO's to traders and brokers, all-too-tempting lucrative financial incentives existed for performance in the financial industry.<br />\nThe past widespread financial misconduct led to a call for financial reform. The [[Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]]  was passed in 2010 to increase accountability and transparency in the financial industry and protect consumers from deceptive financial practices.<ref>Ferrell, Fraedrich: ''Business Ethics'', ''eleventh edition'' Ethical Decision Making and Case, Sexual Harassment in Workplace. February 17, 2017. p. 80</ref> [[Domestic inquiry]]  A domestic inquiry typically follows a \u2018show cause\u2019 letter, which is sent to the employee requesting an explanation for the alleged misconduct. If the response is not satisfactory, the employer will move to the more formal domestic inquiry. Domestic inquiry should be carried out as soon as possible following accusations of misconduct and all activities should be formalized and recorded in full. Legally it is important than the investigation be carried out objectively \u2013 the investigating officers, for example, should be unconnected to the incident, and the employee should be given full opportunity to state their own case and present evidence in their favor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pesaraonline.net/domestic-inquiry.htm|title=Domestic Inquiry|website=pesaraonline.net|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> Union representatives or colleagues should be allowed to sit in during the process if the employer requests their presence, although the employee can't insist on legal representation. An employer may, on the grounds of misconduct inconsistent with the fulfillment of the express or implied conditions of his services, after due inquiry:\n# dismiss without notice the employee\n# downgrade the employee\n# impose any other lesser punishment as he deems just and fit, and where a punishment of suspension without wages is imposed, it shall not exceed a period of two weeks.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* {{cite book |last = Ghaiye |first = B. R. |title = Misconduct in Employment |publisher=EBC |ISBN = 9789351450252 |edition = Hardbound }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{cite news |publisher=FBI |work=Law Enforcement Bulletin |url = https://www.fbi.gov/stats-services/publications/law-enforcement-bulletin/2013/March/research-forum |date=March 2013 |title=Research Forum }}\n\n{{-}}\n{{abuse}}\n\n[[Category:Misconduct| ]]\n[[Category:Legal terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Scholar765", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link to other Wikipedia pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misconduct"}
{"title_page": "Saint Alban's Cross", "text_new": "[[File:Saint Alban's cross.svg|thumb|275px|right|Cross of St Alban]]\n[[File:Flag of Mercia (2014).svg|thumb|275px|right|Flag of Mercia (Flag Institute)]]\n\nThe '''Saint Alban's Cross''' is a yellow [[saltire]] on a blue field (''azure a saltire or''). It is found in several flags, notably that of the [[St. Alban's Cathedral|Cathedral and Abbey Church of St Alban]], previously a [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] monastery, and the city of [[St Albans]], [[Hertfordshire]]. \n\nIt is the heraldic emblem that is commonly [[attributed arms|attributed]] to the Anglo-Saxon [[Kingdom of Mercia]]. A saltire is attributed to Mercia in College of Arms Ms. L.14, dating from the reign of [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] (d. 1272).\nThe arms were subsequently{{year needed|date=March 2019}} used by the [[St Albans Cathedral|Abbey of St Albans]]. With the dissolution of the Abbey and the incorporation of the borough of [[St Albans]] the device was used on the town's corporate seal and was officially recorded as the arms of the town at an [[heraldic visitation]] in 1634.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civicheraldry.co.uk/herts.html|title=CIVIC HERALDRY OF ENGLAND AND WALES - HERTFORDSHIRE|website=www.civicheraldry.co.uk}}</ref> The cross has also been incorporated into a number of [[coat of arms|coats of arms]], such as [[Hertfordshire County Council|Hertfordshire county council]] and those of Mercian towns, including [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]] and [[Blaby]]. Display of the Saint Alban's Cross in flags is modern. Such flags are flown{{year needed|date=March 2019}} from [[Tamworth Castle]]. The flag was flown outside [[Council House, Birmingham|Birmingham Council House]] during 2009 while the [[Staffordshire Hoard]] was on display in the city, and is shown in street signs in [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], the \"ancient capital of Mercia\".\n\nIt is possible that the colours of the cross and connection with [[Saint Alban]] is partly through a link with [[Saint Andrew]]; a chapel of Saint Andrew was from an early period attached to the Abbey of Saint Alban, and this may be part of the origin of the design.<ref>Middlesex & Hertfordshire Notes and Queries, v. 3 (1897), [https://archive.org/details/middlesexhertfo01unkngoog/page/n123 p. 96].</ref>\n\nThe darker variant of the Cross of St Alban was officially registered by the [[Flag Institute]] as the Flag of Mercia in 2014. The Flag Institute's own rules do not allow an identical flag being recognised for two different polities, and since the Cross of St Alban had already been registered for the City of St Albans, it could not be used for Mercia. Eventually the Institute decided to adopt the darker variant, as this tends to better match actual flags flown to represent Mercia, such as the one on Tamworth Castle.<ref>[https://www.flaginstitute.org/wp/flags/mercia/ Flag Institute: Mercia, St Alban's Cross].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mercia#Attributed_heraldry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cross symbols]]\n[[Category:Flags of saints|Alban]]\n[[Category:Saltire flags]]\n[[Category:Crosses in heraldry]]\n[[Category:Mercia]]\n\n{{flag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Saint Alban's cross.svg|thumb|275px|right|Cross of St Alban]]\n[[File:Flag of Mercia (2014).svg|thumb|275px|right|Flag of Mercia (Flag Institute)]]\n\nThe '''Saint Alban's Cross''' is a yellow [[saltire]] on a blue field (''azure a saltire or''). It is found in several flags, notably that of the [[St. Alban's Cathedral|Cathedral and Abbey Church of St Alban]], previously a [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] monastery, and the city of [[St Albans]], [[Hertfordshire]]. \n\nIt is the heraldic emblem that is commonly [[attributed arms|attributed]] to the Anglo-Saxon [[Kingdom of Mercia]]. A saltire is attributed to Mercia in College of Arms Ms. L.14, dating from the reign of [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] (d. 1272).\nThe arms were subsequently{{year needed|date=March 2019}} used by the [[St Albans Cathedral|Abbey of St Albans]]. With the dissolution of the Abbey and the incorporation of the borough of [[St Albans]] the device was used on the town's corporate seal and was officially recorded as the arms of the town at an [[heraldic visitation]] in 1634.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civicheraldry.co.uk/herts.html|title=CIVIC HERALDRY OF ENGLAND AND WALES - HERTFORDSHIRE|website=www.civicheraldry.co.uk}}</ref> The cross has also been incorporated into a number of [[coat of arms|coats of arms]] of Mercian towns, including [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], [[Leek, Staffordshire|Leek]] and [[Blaby]]. Display of the Saint Alban's Cross in flags is modern. Such flags are flown{{year needed|date=March 2019}} from [[Tamworth Castle]]. The flag was flown outside [[Council House, Birmingham|Birmingham Council House]] during 2009 while the [[Staffordshire Hoard]] was on display in the city, and is shown in street signs in  [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], the \"ancient capital of Mercia\".\n\nIt is possible that the colours of the cross and connection with [[Saint Alban]] is partly through a link with [[Saint Andrew]]; a chapel of Saint Andrew was from an early period attached to the Abbey of Saint Alban, and this may be part of the origin of the design.<ref>Middlesex & Hertfordshire Notes and Queries, v. 3 (1897), [https://archive.org/details/middlesexhertfo01unkngoog/page/n123 p. 96].</ref>\n\nThe darker variant of the Cross of St Alban was officially registered by the [[Flag Institute]] as the Flag of Mercia in 2014. The Flag Institute's own rules do not allow an identical flag being recognised for two different polities, and since the Cross of St Alban had already been registered for the City of St Albans, it could not be used for Mercia. Eventually the Institute decided to adopt the darker variant, as this tends to better match actual flags flown to represent Mercia, such as the one on Tamworth Castle.<ref>[https://www.flaginstitute.org/wp/flags/mercia/ Flag Institute: Mercia, St Alban's Cross].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mercia#Attributed_heraldry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cross symbols]]\n[[Category:Flags of saints|Alban]]\n[[Category:Saltire flags]]\n[[Category:Crosses in heraldry]]\n[[Category:Mercia]]\n\n{{flag-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pie Ro Cinderton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added that the cross is also on the coat of arms of Hertfordshire county council and removed a double space.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Alban%27s_Cross"}
{"title_page": "Knowle, West Midlands", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                England\n|official_name=           Knowle\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.388093|-1.73181|display=inline,title}}\n|civil_parish=\n| population =69,420\n| population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001]].Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13689796&c=Knowle&d=14&e=62&g=6367047&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1450277481422&enc=1|title=Solihull Ward population 2011|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n |metropolitan_borough=     [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull|Solihull]]\n|region=                   West Midlands\n|metropolitan_county=      [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Meriden (UK Parliament constituency)|Meriden]]\n|post_town= Solihull\n|postcode_district = B93\n|postcode_area= B\n|dial_code=01564\n|os_grid_reference=     SP182767\n|static_image_name= knowle highstreet.JPG\n|static_image_caption=  High Street in 2006\n}}\n'''Knowle''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|o\u028a|l}} is a large village situated 3 miles (5&nbsp;km) east-southeast of the town of [[Solihull]], West Midlands, England. Knowle lies within the [[Historic counties of England|historic county boundaries]] of [[Warwickshire]], and since 1974 it has been part of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull]] within the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]. It lies a few miles from the modern Warwickshire border and has a population of around 11,000 residents.\n\nKnowle is in the [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] of [[Meriden (UK Parliament constituency)|Meriden]].\n\n==Present day==\nKnowle still retains a considerable village charm, despite being on the outer edge of the [[West Midlands conurbation]]. It is contiguous to the south with the similar-sized communities of [[Dorridge]] and [[Bentley Heath]], both of which are mainly residential in nature. The district of Copt Heath is a suburb of Knowle to the north. The village is generally considered to be amongst the most prosperous areas in the English Midlands.\n\n===Shops and businesses===\nKnowle has many shops. Most of these are located on the High Street, though there are a number of side roads and a shopping precinct. Knowle Library is maintained by Solihull Council in a building called Chester House dating back to Tudor times. At the rear of the building a [[Knot garden]] has been restored. The small shopping area also has restaurants of all varieties, making Knowle a popular destination for dining out. In 2011 a [[Costa Coffee]] opened on the High Street. Tesco retains a medium-sized 'Metro' store in St. John's shopping precinct.\n\n===Recreation===\nKnowle is near to the [[Grand Union Canal]] which links Birmingham to London. Knowle Locks are a flight of five locks (originally six until around 1930) near the canal bridge on Kenilworth Road. Recreation areas include Knowle Park, which has a children's play area, tennis courts, football field and plenty of open space. There is also another children's playing field owned by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] near Knowle Primary School, and in the smaller village of Bentley Heath, there is a newly refurbished park, near the highly rated school, of the same name. There is also [[Knowle F.C.]], [[Knowle Village Cricket Club]] who play in Division 2 of the [[Warwickshire Cricket League]], after 3 promotions in three years, and the exclusive Copt Heath Golf Club. The Silhillians Sports Club is nearby, the home venue of [[Silhillians Rugby Union Football Club]] which is the home of Warwickshire Hockey as well as Old Silhillians Hockey Club.\n\nThere are also many clubs in the village for all ages. There are various [[The Scout Association|Scout]] and [[Girlguiding UK|Guide]] groups including a karate class and church groups. The Knowle Society exists to help maintain the village and its heritage. Knowle Local History Society also holds a wealth of historical information about the village and its people from very early times. Knowle also has drama groups and a Village Hall and Knowle and Dorridge Round Table meet locally.\n\n===Housing and schools=== \nKnowle has two schools, a [[Church of England]] primary school with a nursery and a secondary school, [[Arden School]], which also caters for [[Dorridge]] and [[Bentley Heath]]. In September 2006, a [[sixth form centre]] commenced with over 50 students. The project cost approximately \u00a34 million and has attracted students from many of the surrounding schools. A new design and technology block called \u2018The Smart Centre\u2019 has also been recently completed with another similar building which has also recently been completed. They are considered to be well performing schools, even considering the advantaged catchment area.\n[[File:Knowle Church.jpg|thumb|right|[[Knowle Parish Church|Church of St. John the Baptist, St. Lawrence and St. Anne]]]]\nThe main church is a [[Church of England]] Parish Church and there is a [[United Reformed Church]] on Station Road. The Parish Church offers many services using modern equipment, the old Guild house and much newer St. John's Hall.\n\nThe housing in Knowle is mainly detached or semi-detached with the occasional terraced street and some apartment blocks. More recently, developers have bought up housing for demolition and are building \"windfall developments\" of apartments on its outskirts. House prices are considerably higher than the national average due to the demand for housing in the highly affluent southeastern fringes of the West Midlands conurbation and high achieving schools.\n\n==Community Groups==\nThe village has strong local community organisations, including the Knowle Society, a Neighbourhood Forum, Round Table, Lions, and several Scout groups.\n\n===Neighbourhood Forum===\nKnowle, Dorridge and Bentley Heath Neighbourhood Forum was formed in 2015 with the purpose of bringing together the people from the three adjoining villages to define how they would like to see the villages develop in the future.  The Forum will collate the policies developed into a draft Neighbourhood Plan for the three villages during 2017, and subsequently arrange for a local referendum to create the Neighbourhood Plan as a statutory planning document for the area.  The Forum is run entirely by volunteers, and by Spring 2017 had a membership of over 800.\n\n==Transport==\nThe village lies on the [[A4141 road]] and is close to the [[M42 motorway]]. Knowle does not have its own railway station, but nearby [[Dorridge railway station]], on the [[Chiltern Main Line]], was previously known as ''Knowle and Dorridge'' and for a period just as' 'Knowle' '. Another station lies a few miles north at [[Hampton-in-Arden railway station|Hampton-in-Arden]] on the Coventry-Birmingham ([[West Coast Main Line|West Coast]]) line and [[Birmingham International railway station]] is nearby for express services to [[Euston railway station|London Euston]]. Knowle is also close to [[Birmingham Airport]] and is linked to [[Solihull]] by bus service S3. Junction 5 of the [[M42 motorway]] runs a little over a mile from the western edge of the village.\n\nThe [[Grand Union Canal]] Birmingham Main Line lies to the east of Knowle, between [[Birmingham]] to the north and [[Leamington Spa]] to the south and east.\n\n==Nearby places of interest==\nSurrounding villages include Bentley Heath, [[Dorridge]], [[Hampton-in-Arden]], [[Balsall Common]], [[Hockley Heath]] and [[Henley-in-Arden]]. To the northwest is [[Solihull]] and [[Birmingham]], to the east [[Coventry]], and to the south [[Warwick]], [[Leamington Spa]] and, further afield, [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].\n\n==Notable residents==\n{{more citations needed section|date=September 2011}}\n\n*[[Jasper Carrott]], comedian\n*[[Karren Brady]], businesswoman\n*[[John Wyndham]], Science fiction writer<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2004/aug/26/sciencefictionspecial.sciencefictionfantasyandhorror The war of the words | Science | The Guardian]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.knowlefunrun.org.uk Knowle Fun Run] organised by\n*[http://www.knowleanddorridgelions.com Knowle and Dorridge Lions]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190121163611/http://www.knowleseascouts.org.uk/ Knowle Sea Scout Group]\n*[http://www.yokbc.co.uk Ye Olde Knowle Bowling Club]\n*[http://www.knowleparishchurch.org.uk/ Knowle Parish Church website]\n*[http://www.knowlehistory.org.uk/ Knowle Local History Society website]\n*[http://www.kandd.org.uk/ Knowle and Dorridge Round Table]\n*[http://www.1stknowlescouts.com/ 1st Knowle Scout Group]\n*[http://www.knowlevillage.play-cricket.com Knowle Village Cricket Club]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Solihull]]\n[[Category:Conservation areas in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                England\n|official_name=           Knowle\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.388093|-1.73181|display=inline,title}}\n|civil_parish=\n| population =10,678\n| population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001]].Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13689796&c=Knowle&d=14&e=62&g=6367047&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1450277481422&enc=1|title=Solihull Ward population 2011|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n |metropolitan_borough=     [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull|Solihull]]\n|region=                   West Midlands\n|metropolitan_county=      [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Meriden (UK Parliament constituency)|Meriden]]\n|post_town= Solihull\n|postcode_district = B93\n|postcode_area= B\n|dial_code=01564\n|os_grid_reference=     SP182767\n|static_image_name= knowle highstreet.JPG\n|static_image_caption=  High Street in 2006\n}}\n'''Knowle''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|o\u028a|l}} is a large village situated 3 miles (5&nbsp;km) east-southeast of the town of [[Solihull]], West Midlands, England. Knowle lies within the [[Historic counties of England|historic county boundaries]] of [[Warwickshire]], and since 1974 it has been part of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull]] within the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]. It lies a few miles from the modern Warwickshire border and has a population of around 11,000 residents.\n\nKnowle is in the [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] of [[Meriden (UK Parliament constituency)|Meriden]].\n\n==Present day==\nKnowle still retains a considerable village charm, despite being on the outer edge of the [[West Midlands conurbation]]. It is contiguous to the south with the similar-sized communities of [[Dorridge]] and [[Bentley Heath]], both of which are mainly residential in nature. The district of Copt Heath is a suburb of Knowle to the north. The village is generally considered to be amongst the most prosperous areas in the English Midlands.\n\n===Shops and businesses===\nKnowle has many shops. Most of these are located on the High Street, though there are a number of side roads and a shopping precinct. Knowle Library is maintained by Solihull Council in a building called Chester House dating back to Tudor times. At the rear of the building a [[Knot garden]] has been restored. The small shopping area also has restaurants of all varieties, making Knowle a popular destination for dining out. In 2011 a [[Costa Coffee]] opened on the High Street. Tesco retains a medium-sized 'Metro' store in St. John's shopping precinct.\n\n===Recreation===\nKnowle is near to the [[Grand Union Canal]] which links Birmingham to London. Knowle Locks are a flight of five locks (originally six until around 1930) near the canal bridge on Kenilworth Road. Recreation areas include Knowle Park, which has a children's play area, tennis courts, football field and plenty of open space. There is also another children's playing field owned by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] near Knowle Primary School, and in the smaller village of Bentley Heath, there is a newly refurbished park, near the highly rated school, of the same name. There is also [[Knowle F.C.]], [[Knowle Village Cricket Club]] who play in Division 2 of the [[Warwickshire Cricket League]], after 3 promotions in three years, and the exclusive Copt Heath Golf Club. The Silhillians Sports Club is nearby, the home venue of [[Silhillians Rugby Union Football Club]] which is the home of Warwickshire Hockey as well as Old Silhillians Hockey Club.\n\nThere are also many clubs in the village for all ages. There are various [[The Scout Association|Scout]] and [[Girlguiding UK|Guide]] groups including a karate class and church groups. The Knowle Society exists to help maintain the village and its heritage. Knowle Local History Society also holds a wealth of historical information about the village and its people from very early times. Knowle also has drama groups and a Village Hall and Knowle and Dorridge Round Table meet locally.\n\n===Housing and schools=== \nKnowle has two schools, a [[Church of England]] primary school with a nursery and a secondary school, [[Arden School]], which also caters for [[Dorridge]] and [[Bentley Heath]]. In September 2006, a [[sixth form centre]] commenced with over 50 students. The project cost approximately \u00a34 million and has attracted students from many of the surrounding schools. A new design and technology block called \u2018The Smart Centre\u2019 has also been recently completed with another similar building which has also recently been completed. They are considered to be well performing schools, even considering the advantaged catchment area.\n[[File:Knowle Church.jpg|thumb|right|[[Knowle Parish Church|Church of St. John the Baptist, St. Lawrence and St. Anne]]]]\nThe main church is a [[Church of England]] Parish Church and there is a [[United Reformed Church]] on Station Road. The Parish Church offers many services using modern equipment, the old Guild house and much newer St. John's Hall.\n\nThe housing in Knowle is mainly detached or semi-detached with the occasional terraced street and some apartment blocks. More recently, developers have bought up housing for demolition and are building \"windfall developments\" of apartments on its outskirts. House prices are considerably higher than the national average due to the demand for housing in the highly affluent southeastern fringes of the West Midlands conurbation and high achieving schools.\n\n==Community Groups==\nThe village has strong local community organisations, including the Knowle Society, a Neighbourhood Forum, Round Table, Lions, and several Scout groups.\n\n===Neighbourhood Forum===\nKnowle, Dorridge and Bentley Heath Neighbourhood Forum was formed in 2015 with the purpose of bringing together the people from the three adjoining villages to define how they would like to see the villages develop in the future.  The Forum will collate the policies developed into a draft Neighbourhood Plan for the three villages during 2017, and subsequently arrange for a local referendum to create the Neighbourhood Plan as a statutory planning document for the area.  The Forum is run entirely by volunteers, and by Spring 2017 had a membership of over 800.\n\n==Transport==\nThe village lies on the [[A4141 road]] and is close to the [[M42 motorway]]. Knowle does not have its own railway station, but nearby [[Dorridge railway station]], on the [[Chiltern Main Line]], was previously known as ''Knowle and Dorridge'' and for a period just as' 'Knowle' '. Another station lies a few miles north at [[Hampton-in-Arden railway station|Hampton-in-Arden]] on the Coventry-Birmingham ([[West Coast Main Line|West Coast]]) line and [[Birmingham International railway station]] is nearby for express services to [[Euston railway station|London Euston]]. Knowle is also close to [[Birmingham Airport]] and is linked to [[Solihull]] by bus service S3. Junction 5 of the [[M42 motorway]] runs a little over a mile from the western edge of the village.\n\nThe [[Grand Union Canal]] Birmingham Main Line lies to the east of Knowle, between [[Birmingham]] to the north and [[Leamington Spa]] to the south and east.\n\n==Nearby places of interest==\nSurrounding villages include Bentley Heath, [[Dorridge]], [[Hampton-in-Arden]], [[Balsall Common]], [[Hockley Heath]] and [[Henley-in-Arden]]. To the northwest is [[Solihull]] and [[Birmingham]], to the east [[Coventry]], and to the south [[Warwick]], [[Leamington Spa]] and, further afield, [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].\n\n==Notable residents==\n{{more citations needed section|date=September 2011}}\n\n*[[Jasper Carrott]], comedian\n*[[Karren Brady]], businesswoman\n*[[John Wyndham]], Science fiction writer<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2004/aug/26/sciencefictionspecial.sciencefictionfantasyandhorror The war of the words | Science | The Guardian]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.knowlefunrun.org.uk Knowle Fun Run] organised by\n*[http://www.knowleanddorridgelions.com Knowle and Dorridge Lions]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190121163611/http://www.knowleseascouts.org.uk/ Knowle Sea Scout Group]\n*[http://www.yokbc.co.uk Ye Olde Knowle Bowling Club]\n*[http://www.knowleparishchurch.org.uk/ Knowle Parish Church website]\n*[http://www.knowlehistory.org.uk/ Knowle Local History Society website]\n*[http://www.kandd.org.uk/ Knowle and Dorridge Round Table]\n*[http://www.1stknowlescouts.com/ 1st Knowle Scout Group]\n*[http://www.knowlevillage.play-cricket.com Knowle Village Cricket Club]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Solihull]]\n[[Category:Conservation areas in 